Exploring Montana fires with MTBS and PRISM climate data

Author

Travis Belote

Introduction

Fire plays a critical role in ecosystems of Montana, influencing both nature and society. We will be pulling in several different kinds of data to explore patterns of fire size, total area burned, fire severity, and climate in Montana. MTBS data are available at https://www.mtbs.gov/. Researchers use remotely sensed data to estimate fire severity by looking at the difference between conditions from before and after a fire. They then classify these data into 5 severity classes: un-burned = dark green; low severity = light green, moderate severity = yellow; high severity = red; increased greenness = not shown in below). The example below is from the Bridger Foothills fire in September 2020.

Images above. MTBS data of the Bridger Foothills fire from September of 2020, and photo of smoke from the fire.

Before bringing in and analyzing data, we need to load our libraries. Here, Iâm using the terra and sf packages to work with spatial data and several packages (dplyr and gglot) within the tidyverse.

We will be working with 3 primary forms of data: vector data (polygons of fires), tabular data (in a spreadsheet), and raster data (PRISM climate data). Letâs start with bringing in fire perimeters from MTBS data, clipping it to Montana, recalculating area for each fire, plotting the data, and considering the consequences of the patterns.

Note: I use âpipesâ which look like this %>%. This makes code more readable and can be read like a sentence. The beginning of a pipe (the object) is like the subject of a sentence and the functions are like the verbs. This structure makes the code easier to read. I donât always use this approach, but do when I can.

# use vect from the terra package to read in the shapefile
MTfires_100kmBuffer <- vect("C:/Users/tbelote/TWS Dropbox/Travis Belote/MT_fire_demo/Montana_MTBS_fires_1948_2024.shp")

# Load in a map of the boundary of Montana 
mt <- vect("C:/Users/tbelote/TWS Dropbox/Travis Belote/MT_fire_demo/Montana.shp")

# The two datasets do not have the same coorrdinate reference system (crs)
# Project the map of Montana to the same coordinate system as the fire data
mt_prj1 <- mt %>% terra::project(MTfires_100kmBuffer)

# use the new projected boundary of Montana to "clip" the fire data that includes 
# some of Idaho and Wyoming; here I'm using "intersect" from the terra package
MT_fires <- MTfires_100kmBuffer %>% terra::intersect(mt_prj1)

# look at the map of Montana fires
terra::plot(MT_fires, col = "red")

Some fires straddled the state borders, so we need to recalculate total area so that the area in the tabular data match the area in the spatial data. We need to reproject to an projection that minimizes distoration, so Iâm going back to the original projection of Montana.

MT_fires_prj <- MT_fires %>% project(mt)

# I'm using 'expanse' to calculate area (square km) for each polygon

MT_fires_prj$calc_area_km2 <- expanse(MT_fires_prj, unit = "km")

Fire size distributions

The size of fires obviously has a large affect on ecosystems and human communities. Understanding the factors that govern the size of fires has been the topic of much research. Scientists have studied how fire sizes are influenced by the continuity of fuels, long-term and broad-scale climate, and daily weather events. Forests with contiguous interlocking tree canopies have been described as âcontagious landscapesâ where a fire can easily spread. Creating heterogeneity in the canopy is a goal to enhance forest resilience. Long-term increases in temperature and decreases in precipitation create dry conditions and can lead to bigger fire years. Daily wind events can also play a huge role in fire spread.

Letâs look at the distributions of fire sizes in Montana from 1984 to 2024.

# Let's look at a histogram of the burned area. 
# We can do this very easily using hist()
hist(MT_fires_prj$calc_area_km2, col = "red", xlab=("Size of fire (sq. km)"), main = NA)

# Lots of small fires and a few big ones, as we might expect

It might be interesting to look at a how the distribution of fire sizes vary by year, so Iâm going to move over to ggplot and use âfacet_wrapâ which will create a new histogram for each year. ggplot wants the data as a dataframe, so I have to use âas.data.frameâ as the first step.

MT_fires_prj %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
  ggplot() + geom_histogram(aes(calc_area_km2)) + facet_wrap("year") + theme_bw()
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Iâm interested in the Pareto Principle, which colloquially has been called the 80/20 rule. There are many phenomena where an important few (top 20%) have a disproportionate affect on an outcome (80%). This has been applied to business (20% of customers generate 80% of revenues), to daily lives (we wear 20% of our clothes 80% of the time), to ecosystems (20% of the species contribute 80% of the biomass).

This thinking has also been applied to fires: 20% of the fires burn 80% of the area. Letâs look to see if this is true in Montana. First, we need to arrange our fires from largest to smallest (arrange in descending order), then we want to calculate the cumulative area burned starting with the largest fire, then the second largest fire, etc. Finally, weâll calculate how each of these fires contribute to the total area burned. Weâll then create a Pareto plot and calculate some summary statistics.

# Prepare data: Calculate cumulative percentages and sort explicitly
MT_fires_df <- as.data.frame(MT_fires_prj) %>%
  arrange(desc(calc_area_km2)) %>%
  mutate(fire_order = factor(row_number(), levels = row_number()), # Explicit order
    cumulative_area = cumsum(calc_area_km2),
    cumulative_percentage = cumulative_area / sum(calc_area_km2) * 100)

# Create Pareto plot
ggplot(MT_fires_df, aes(x = fire_order)) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = calc_area_km2), stat = "identity", fill = "red") +
  geom_point(aes(y = cumulative_percentage / 100 * max(calc_area_km2)), color = "black", cex = 0.5) +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Fire size (sq. km)",
    sec.axis = sec_axis(~ . / max(MT_fires_df$calc_area_km2) * 100, name = "Cumulative Percentage (%)")) +
  labs(title = "Pareto plot (80/20 rule?)", x = "Fires (Ordered by Size)", y = NULL) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(), axis.ticks.x = element_blank()) + 
    theme_classic()

From the figure above, we found that the largest 20% of fires make up 74% of the area burned. Why might that be the case?

Now that we have these data summarized, we want to create a plot of total area burned (TAB) across years. Weâre going to use ggplot2, which is part of the tidyverse. Weâre going to use pipes again to start this line of code. geom_line tells R to make a line of the data with year on the x-axis and TAB on the y-axis. aes means aesthetics mapping and describes the visual properties to be graphed.

total_area %>% ggplot() + geom_line(aes(x = year, y = TAB))

That looks okay, but I want to customize the plot by turning the line red, removing the grey background, and make the y-axis label more meaningful.

total_area %>% ggplot() + geom_line(aes(x = year, y = TAB), color = "red") +

Are there any problems with looking at these patterns?

I mentioned that MTBS scientists classify âun-burnedâ areas within fire perimeters. Should we count these areas as âburnedâ? Letâs remove the un-burned areas and re-plot the data. Weâre going to start from our original data called severity and first filter by Class using != say ânot equal toâ so weâre basically going to ignore the un-burned area, then group by year, and sum the burned area into a new TAB. Weâre going to pipe this right to our plot instead of creating a new dataframe as we did before.

severity %>% filter(Class != 1) %>% group_by(year)  %>% summarize(TAB = sum(Area_km2)) %>% ggplot() + geom_line(aes(x = year, y = TAB), color = "red") + 
  theme_classic() + 
  ylab("Total area burned (square km) without un-burned")

What do you notice about this new plot that excludes the un-burned areas?

Climate and fire

We know that the total area burned and the % of fires classified as high severity vary from year to year? What might explain these patterns? Weâll investigate the possible relationship between total area burned and total precipitation. Iâve already downloaded PRISM precipitation data for the lower 48 states. PRISM stands for Parameter-elevation Regressions on Independent Slopes Model - and is a type of climate data widely used - but be careful because there are critics of its approach to downscaling climate data. Explore the data here: https://prism.oregonstate.edu/

Weâre going to bring the annual precipitation (mm) into R and then clip out on the data for Montana. I will be reading in the annual precipitation data for Montana using rast from the terra package and âstackingâ the rasters. Stacking rasters with the same resolution, extent, and coordinate system is a very powerful way to analyze spatial data. Since there are many datasets listed in âppt_filesâ rast will create a stack of layers.

# Set the directory where the .bil files are stored
ppt_dir <- "C:/Users/tbelote/TWS Dropbox/Travis Belote/PRISM_r/annual_ppt_1984_2023"

# Get a list of all .bil files in the directory
ppt_files <- list.files(list.files(ppt_dir, pattern = "bil$", full.names = TRUE), pattern = "bil$", full.names = TRUE)

# Load the .bil files into a SpatRaster stack (to work with them as a time series)
ppt_stack <- rast(ppt_files)

# Load in a map of the boundary of Montana 
mt <- st_read("C:/Users/tbelote/TWS Dropbox/Travis Belote/MT_fire_demo/Montana.shp")

ppt_MT <- ppt_stack %>% crop(mt) %>% mask(mt) %>% trim()

# Calculate the mean annual precipitation for Montana
mean_ppt <- ppt_MT %>% global(stat = "mean", na.rm = TRUE) %>% as.data.frame()

# The approach above makes year the row name (not a column in the data), 
# so I need to use rownames_to_column() to make year a variable. 
# I also want to turn it into a number so I can use year as a 
# quantitative variable for plotting.
annual_ppt <- rownames_to_column(mean_ppt, var = "year")
annual_ppt$year <- as.numeric(annual_ppt$year)

# Finally, let's plot how annual precipitation (averaged across Montana) varies year-to-year.
annual_ppt %>% ggplot() + 
  geom_line(aes(x = year, y = mean), color = "blue") +
  theme_classic() +
  ylab("Annual precipitation - average for Montana (mm)")

We now have year, total area burned, the proportion of fire classified as high severity, and annual precipitation across Montana. We want to explore some climate-fire relationships, but we need to join these data up. Luckily, our data all correspond to Montana, and all datasets include year as a variable. Weâll need to join these data together. Joining data in a relational database is a very powerful approach to asking novel research questions with existing datasets.

Before you run this code, what would you predict the relationship between annual precipitation and total area burned might be? What about annual precipitation and proportion of fires that burned as high severity?

# "You can "pipe" together two left_join functions to add annual_ppt to our total area burned data, then add high_severity. 
tab_high_sev_ppt <- total_area %>% left_join(annual_ppt, by = 'year') %>% 
  left_join(high_severity, by = "year")
